om it.<br /><br />Why would we have to protect the kernel from EFI?<br /><br />If we can't trust EFI, then the machine is already compromised. We<br />just *called* an EFI routine, if EFI is untrusted, it did something<br />random.<br /><br />I mean, it could have already done something bad at boot time when it<br />loaded the kernel.<br /><br />So no, let's not "protect ourselves from EFI".<br /><br />             Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
